akthrough Act]]\n|-\n|valign=top|\n*'''[[Fine Young Cannibals]]'''\n**[[Erasure]]\n**[[Eurythmics]]\n**[[Simply Red]]\n**[[Soul II Soul]]\n**[[Tears for Fears]]\n|valign=top|\n*'''[[Lisa Stansfield]]'''\n**[[The Beautiful South]]\n**[[Shakespears Sister]]\n**[[Soul II Soul]]\n**[[The Stone Roses]]\n|-\n! width=\"50%\"|Outstanding Contribution to Music<br/><small>(presented by [[Terry Ellis (record producer)|Terry Ellis]])</small>\n! width=\"50%\"|[[Brit Award for International Solo Artist|International Solo Artist]]<br/><small>(presented by [[Adam Ant]])</small>\n|-\n|valign=top|\n*'''[[Queen (band)|Queen]]'''\n|valign=top|\n*'''[[Neneh Cherry]]'''\n**[[Bobby Brown]]\n**[[Gloria Estefan]]\n**[[Prince (musician)|Prince]]\n**[[Tina Turner]]\n|-\n! width=\"50%\"|[[Brit Award for International Group|International Group]]<br/><small>(presented by [[Ray Davies]])</small>\n! width=\"50%\"|[[Brit Award for International Breakthrough Act|International Breakthrough Act]]\n|-\n| valign=top|\n*'''[[U2]]'''\n**[[Bon Jovi]]\n**[[De La Soul]]\n**[[Gipsy Kings]]\n**[[Guns N' Roses]]\n**[[Milli Vanilli]]\n|valign=\"top|\n*'''[[Neneh Cherry]]'''\n**[[Bobby Brown]]\n**[[De La Soul]]\n**[[Guns N' Roses]]\n**[[Paula Abdul]]\n|-\n! width=\"50%\"|[[Brit Award for Classical Recording|Classical Recording]]\n! width=\"50%\"|[[Brit Award for Soundtrack/Cast Recording|Soundtrack/Cast Recording]]\n|-\n|valign=top|\n*'''[[Simon Rattle]]'''\n**[[Jeffrey Tate]]\n**[[John Eliot Gardiner]]\n**[[Nigel Kennedy]]\n**[[Riccardo Chailly]]\n|valign=top|\n*'''[[Batman (1989 film)|Batman]]'''\n**[[Aspects of Love]]\n**[[Beaches (film)|Beaches]]\n**[[Henry V (1989 film)|Henry V]]\n**[[The Cook, the Thief, His Wife and Her Lover]]\n|}\n\n==Multiple nominations and awards==\nThe following artists received multiple awards and/or nominations. don't counting Outstanding Contribution to Music.\n[[File:Tauron Nowa Muzyka 2014 - Neneh Cherry (06).jpg|right|200px|upright|thumb|alt=|Two-time winner [[Neneh Cherry]]]]\n{{col-float}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Artists that received multiple nominations\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:55px;\" |Nominations\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |Artist\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|4\n|[[Lisa Stansfield]]\n|-\n|[[Soul II Soul]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|3\n|[[De La Soul]]\n|-\n|[[Eurythmics]]\n|-\n|[[Jive Bunny and the Mastermixers]]\n|-\n|[[Neneh Cherry]]\n|-\n|[[Simply Red]]\n|-\n|[[Tears for Fears]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"10\"|2\n|[[The Beautiful South]]\n|-\n|[[Bobby Brown]]\n|-\n|[[Fine Young Cannibals]]\n|-\n|[[Guns N' Roses]]\n|-\n|[[Holly Johnson]]\n|-\n|[[Jason Donovan]]\n|-\n|[[Kate Bush]]\n|-\n|[[Paul McCartney]]\n|-\n|[[Phil Collins]]\n|-\n|[[Stock Aitken Waterman]]\n|}\n{{col-float-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Artists that received multiple awards\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:55px;\" |Awards\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |Artist\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|2\n|[[Fine Young Cannibals]]\n|-\n|[[Neneh Cherry]]\n|-\n|[[Phil Collins]]\n|}\n{{col-float-end}}\n\n==Notable moments==\n\n===Freddie Mercury===\nThe 1990 awards ceremony saw the last public appearance of [[Queen (band)|Queen]] frontman [[Freddie Mercury]].<ref name=queen>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/events/brit_awards/freddy.htm|title=The Highs and Lows of the Brit Awards|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref> Queen appeared at the ceremony to receive the Brit Award for Outstanding Contribution to British Music.<ref name=queen/><ref>[http://www.brits.co.uk/photo/queen-freddie-mercury-roger-taylor-brian-may-brits-1990 Queen, Freddie Mercury, Roger Taylor, Brian May, BRITS 1990] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140118123708/http://www.brits.co.uk/photo/queen-freddie-mercury-roger-taylor-brian-may-brits-1990|date=18 January 2014}} brits.co.uk Retrieved 28 April 2011.</ref> Mercury (who had been suffering from [[AIDS]] since 1987 but had not disclosed it to the public) did not make a speech, as [[Brian May]] did the talking on behalf of the other members, but his gaunt appearance was noticeable. He briefly thanks the public and wishes them goodnight before Queen leave the stage. Mercury died in November 1991 from complications resulting from AIDS.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ontopmag.com/article/37401/Adam_Lambert_Freddie_Mercury_Would_Be_An_Open_Book_About_Sexuality_In_2018|title=Adam Lambert: Freddie Mercury Would Be An 'Open Book' About Sexuality In 2018|magazine=On Top|date=March 1, 2018|accessdate=March 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.brits.co.uk/history/shows/1990 1990 Brit Awards at Brits.co.uk]\n\n{{Brit Awards}}\n\n[[Category:Brit Awards]]\n[[Category:1990 in British music]]\n[[Category:1990 music awards|BRIT Awards]]\n[[Category:1990 in London|BRIT Awards]]\n[[Category:1990 awards in the United Kingdom|Brit]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox award\n|name = 10th Brit Awards\n|image = \n|date = 18 February 1990\n|venue = [[Dominion Theatre]]\n|host = [[Cathy McGowan (presenter)|Cathy McGowan]]\n| network = [[BBC]]\n|previous = [[1989 Brit Awards|1989]]\n|main = [[Brit Awards]]\n|next = [[1991 Brit Awards|1991]]\n|most_awards = [[Fine Young Cannibals]], [[Neneh Cherry]] and [[Phil Collins]] (2)\n|most_nominations = [[Lisa Stansfield]] and [[Soul II Soul]] (4)\n}}\nThe '''1990 [[Brit Awards]]''' were the 10th edition of the biggest annual [[pop music]] awards in the [[United Kingdom]]. They are run by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] and took place on 18 February 1990. The ceremony was held at the [[Dominion Theatre]] in [[London]] for the first time, having previously been held at the [[Royal Albert Hall]], and was hosted by [[Cathy McGowan (presenter)|Cathy McGowan]].\n\n==Performances==\n*[[Lisa Stansfield]] \u2013 \"[[All Around the Wo