{"title_page": "Philadelphia Charge", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n|clubname   = Philadelphia Charge\n|image      = Philly Charge.PNG\n|image_size = 190px\n|fullname   = \n|nickname   = \n|motto      = \n|shortname  = \n|founded    = 10 April 2000<ref name=founded>{{cite news|url=http://cnnfn.cnn.com/2000/04/10/deals/soccer/|title=Women's soccer in deals|publisher=[[CNNfn]]|date=April 10, 2000|accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref><br />Name established on<br />2 November 2000<ref name=\"founded2000\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/2000-11-03/sports/0011031102_1_zimman-field-soccer-specific-stadiums-franchises|title=Wusa: From Heat To Rays|publisher=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=November 3, 2000|accessdate=October 26, 2013|first=Jerry|last=Trecker}}</ref>\n|dissolved  = 15 September 2003\n|ground     = [[Villanova Stadium]]<br />[[Bryn Mawr, Pennsylvania|Bryn Mawr]], [[Pennsylvania|PA]] [[19010]]\n|capacity   = 12,500\n|chrtitle   = General Manager\n|chairman   = Tim Murphy\n|owner      = [[Comcast]]\n|mgrtitle   = Head Coach\n|manager    = [[Mark Krikorian (soccer)|Mark Krikorian]]\n|league     = [[Women's United Soccer Association]]\n|season   =  Final season<br />2003\n|position =  <br />8th\n|firstgame = \n|largestwin = \n|worstdefeat = \n|topscorer = \n|fansgroup = \n|honours = \n|American = true\n|pattern_la1=_whitelowerthin|pattern_b1=_thinwhitesides|pattern_so1=_band_white|pattern_ra1=_whitelowerthin|leftarm1=EE0000|body1=EE0000|rightarm1=EE0000|shorts1=EE0000|socks1=EE0000\n\n|pattern_la2=|pattern_b2=|pattern_so2=_band_red|pattern_ra2=|leftarm2=FFFFFF|body2=FFFFFF|rightarm2=FFFFFF|shorts2=FFFFFF|socks2=FFFFFF\n}}\n\nThe '''Philadelphia Charge''' was an American women's professional [[soccer]] team that played in the [[Women's United Soccer Association]]. The team played at [[Villanova Stadium]] on the campus of [[Villanova University]] near [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].\n\n==History==\nIn spring of 2000, the newly formed [[Women's United Soccer Association]] (WUSA) announced eight cities were granted franchises to start the league, including [[Philadelphia]].<ref name=founded/> Most of the inaugural teams were owned by major media companies, with the new Philadelphia club operated by locally headquartered [[Comcast Corporation]] who invested an initial $5 million into WUSA.<ref name=founded/><ref name=Comcast>{{cite web |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/stories/2001/04/09/story8.html |title=Women's soccer team ready to Charge |author=John George |website=bizjournals.com |date=9 April 2002 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> In November 2000, the club's name and logo was officially announced as the '''Philadelphia Charge''' and would play home matches at [[Villanova Stadium]].<ref name=Announce>{{cite web |url=https://reuters.screenocean.com/record/167354 |title=USA: SOCCER - INAUGURAL WOMEN'S PROFESSIONAL SOCCER LEAGUE ANNOUNCES TEAM NAMES, LOGOS |publisher=Reuters |date=2 November 2000 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> The logo for the Charge incorporated the Comcast Corp. \"C\" as part of its marketing efforts.<ref name=Comcast/> The Charge began preparations for the first team with a 15-person front office and was supported by the Comcast-Spector organization for stadium operations, marketing, promotions, tickets, and merchandise.<ref name=Comcast/>\n\nBy late 2000, the Charge had announced that [[University of Hartford]] women's soccer coach, [[Mark Krikorian (soccer)|Mark Krikorian]], would be appointed the first head coach of the team.<ref name=HirKrikorian>{{cite web |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2000-11-20-0011201736-story.html |title=KRIKORIAN TO TAKE CHARGE OF PHILADELPHIA FRANCHISE |author=Mark Pukalo |publisher=The Hartford Courant |date=20 November 2000 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> Prior to the start of the season, Krikorian would bring on former Swedish international [[Pia Sundhage]] and [[John Natale]] as assistant coaches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/8769/wusa-notes-assistant-coach-and-front-office-hirin.html |title=WUSA Notes: Assistant coach and front-office hirings |publisher=SoccerAmerica |date=1 February 2001 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Charge would begin their first campaign lead by American forward [[Lorrie Fair]], German defender [[Doris Fitschen]], and English forward [[Kelly Smith]].<ref name=Announce/>\n\n==Players==\nSeveral notable U.S. Women's National Team stars made their pro debuts with the Charge, including defender [[Heather Mitts]] (2001-2003) and goalkeeper [[Hope Solo]], who appeared in 8 matches as a rookie backup goalkeeper in 2003.  Other notables included French international [[Marinette Pichon]], who won the 2002 WUSA Most Valuable Player award for the Charge, and English star [[Kelly Smith]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.funwhileitlasted.net/2012/07/06/june-8-2002-philadelphia-charge-vs-washington-freedom/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-07-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602170941/http://www.funwhileitlasted.net/2012/07/06/june-8-2002-philadelphia-charge-vs-washington-freedom/ |archivedate=2013-06-02 }}</ref>\n\n'''2003 Roster'''<ref>{{cite news|title=2003 Philadelphia Charge Roster|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/wusa/news/2003/philadelphros/|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=21 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=1|nat=USA|pos=GK|name=[[Melissa Moore (soccer)|Melissa Moore]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=2|nat=USA|pos=MF|name=[[Lorrie Fair]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=3|nat=USA|pos=FW|name=[[Emily Burt]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=5|nat=USA|pos=DF|name=[[Karyn Hall]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=6|nat=USA|pos=DF|name=[[Jenny Benson]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=7|nat=FIN|pos=MF|name=[[Anne Makinen]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=8|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Kelly Smith]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=9|nat=CZE|pos=MF|name=[[Pavl\u00edna \u0160\u010dasn\u00e1]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|nat=USA|pos=FW|name=[[Deliah Arrington]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|nat=FRA|pos=FW|name=[[Marinette Pichon]]}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|nat=USA|pos=MF|name=[[Erin Misaki]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|nat=USA|pos=DF|name=[[Heather Mitts]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|nat=USA|pos=MF|name=[[Rachel Kruze]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|nat=USA|pos=MF|name=[[Stacey Tullock]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|nat=DEU|pos=MF|name=[[Melanie Hoffmann]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|nat=USA|pos=GK|name=[[Hope Solo]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=19|nat=USA|pos=DF|name=[[Alexa Borisjuk]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=21|nat=USA|pos=FW|name=[[Trina Maso De Moya]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=22|nat=USA|pos=MF|name=[[Mary McVeigh]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=25|nat=USA|pos=MF|name=[[Jennifer Tietjen-Prozzo]]}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\nCoach: [[Mark Krikorian (soccer)|Mark Krikorian]]\n\n==Year-by-year==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n!  style=\"background:#da2736; color:#FFFFFF; border:2px solid #041C2C; width:50px;\"|Year\n!  style=\"background:#da2736; color:#FFFFFF; border:2px solid #041C2C; width:50px;\"|League\n!  style=\"background:#da2736; color:#FFFFFF; border:2px solid #041C2C; width:125px;\"|Regular Season\n!  style=\"background:#da2736; color:#FFFFFF; border:2px solid #041C2C;\"|P\n!  style=\"background:#da2736; color:#FFFFFF; border:2px solid #041C2C;\"|W\n!  style=\"background:#da2736; color:#FFFFFF; border:2px solid #041C2C;\"|D\n!  style=\"background:#da2736; color:#FFFFFF; border:2px solid #041C2C;\"|L\n!  style=\"background:#da2736; color:#FFFFFF; border:2px solid #041C2C;\"|Pts\n!  style=\"background:#da2736; color:#FFFFFF; border:2px solid #041C2C; width:100px;\"|Playoffs\n!  style=\"background:#da2736; color:#FFFFFF; border:2px solid #041C2C; width:200px;\"|Top Scorer\n!  style=\"background:#da2736; color:#FFFFFF; border:2px solid #041C2C; width:125px;\"|Avg. Attendance\n|-\n|[[2001 Philadelphia Charge season|2001]]\n|[[Women's United Soccer Association|WUSA]]\n|4th Place || 21 || 9 || 4 || 8 || 31\n|Semi-Finals\n|{{flagicon|CHN}} [[Liu Ailing]] (10)\n|7,153\n|-\n|[[2002 Philadelphia Charge season|2002]]\n|[[Women's United Soccer Association|WUSA]]\n|2nd Place || 21 || 11 || 6 || 4 || 39\n|Semi-Finals\n|{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Marinette Pichon]] (14)\n|\n|-\n|[[2003 Philadelphia Charge season|2003]]\n|[[Women's United Soccer Association|WUSA]]\n|8th Place || 21 || 5 || 5 || 11 || 20\n|''Did Not Qualify''\n|{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Marinette Pichon]] (14)\n|\n|}\n<small>Source:[https://www.statscrew.com/womenssoccer/t-WPHC]</small>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2001, Philadelphia Charge player, [[Doris Fitschen]] was named WUSA Defender of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Power forward selected as first WUSA MVP|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/wusa/2001/championship/news/2001/08/23/wusa_awards/|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=21 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Philadelphia Charge player, [[Marinette Pichon]] was named WUSA's Most Valuable Player and Offensive Player of the Year and was the co-recipient with [[Mia Hamm]] for Goal of the Year for a scissor kick volley against the [[San Diego Spirit]]. Goalkeeper [[Melissa Moore (soccer)|Melissa Moore]] was awarded Goalkeeper of the Year and [[Stacey Tullock]] was named Rookie of the Year. Coach [[Mark Krikorian (soccer)|Mark Krikorian]] took the honor of WUSA Coach of the Year the same year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Philadelphia's Pichon takes top honor in WUSA awards|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/wusa/2002-08-22-awards_x.htm|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=21 October 2012|date=22 August 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the Charge was awarded the WUSA Team Fair Play Award and defender, [[Jenny Benson]], was named WUSA Humanitarian of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Meinert wins most valuable player|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/wusa/2003-08-21-wusa-awards_x.htm|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=21 October 2012|date=21 August 2003}}</ref>\n\n==League Suspension==\nThe [[Women's United Soccer Association]] announced on September 15, 2003 that it was suspending operations.<ref>{{cite news|title=WUSA ceases operations after three years|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/wusa/2003-09-15-wusa-folds_x.htm|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=21 October 2012|first1=Vicki|last1=Michaelis|date=16 September 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. WNT Responds to Women's United Soccer Association Suspending Operations|url=http://www.ussoccer.com/news/womens-national-team/2003/09/u-s-wnt-responds-to-womens-united-soccer-association-suspending-operations.aspx|publisher=US Soccer|accessdate=21 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Women's association football|Philadelphia|Sports|Association football}}\n* [[Women's professional sports]]\n* [[List of soccer clubs in the United States]]\n* [[Women's association football]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20011217093641/http://www.wusa.com/charge/ Philadelphia Charge website (archive.org)]\n\n{{Women's United Soccer Association}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct soccer clubs in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Women's soccer clubs in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct sports teams in Philadelphia|Charge]]\n[[Category:Soccer clubs in Philadelphia|C]]\n[[Category:Soccer clubs in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Women's United Soccer Association teams]]\n[[Category:2000 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:2003 disestablishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Charge]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs disestablished in 2003]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 2000]]\n\n\n{{Pennsylvania-footyclub-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football club\n|clubname   = Philadelphia Charge\n|image      = Philly Charge.PNG\n|fullname   = \n|nickname   = \n|motto      = \n|shortname  = \n|founded    = 10 April 2000<ref name=founded>{{cite news|url=http://cnnfn.cnn.com/2000/04/10/deals/soccer/|title=Women's soccer in deals|publisher=[[CNNfn]]|date=April 10, 2000|accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref><br />Name established on<br />2 November 2000<ref name=\"founded2000\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/2000-11-03/sports/0011031102_1_zimman-field-soccer-specific-stadiums-franchises|title=Wusa: From Heat To Rays|publisher=[[Hartford Courant]]|date=November 3, 2000|accessdate=October 26, 2013|first=Jerry|last=Trecker}}</ref>\n|dissolved  = 15 September 2003\n|ground     = [[Villanova Stadium]]<br />[[Bryn Mawr, Pennsylvania|Bryn Mawr]], [[Pennsylvania|PA]] [[19010]]\n|capacity   = 12,500\n|chrtitle   = General Manager\n|chairman   = Tim Murphy\n|owner      = [[Comcast]]\n|mgrtitle   = Head Coach\n|manager    = [[Mark Krikorian (soccer)|Mark Krikorian]]\n|league     = [[Women's United Soccer Association]]\n|season   =  Final season<br />2003\n|position =  <br />8th\n|firstgame = \n|largestwin = \n|worstdefeat = \n|topscorer = \n|fansgroup = \n|honours = \n|American = true\n|pattern_la1=_whitelowerthin|pattern_b1=_thinwhitesides|pattern_so1=_band_white|pattern_ra1=_whitelowerthin|leftarm1=EE0000|body1=EE0000|rightarm1=EE0000|shorts1=EE0000|socks1=EE0000\n\n|pattern_la2=|pattern_b2=|pattern_so2=_band_red|pattern_ra2=|leftarm2=FFFFFF|body2=FFFFFF|rightarm2=FFFFFF|shorts2=FFFFFF|socks2=FFFFFF\n}}\n\nThe '''Philadelphia Charge''' was an American women's professional [[soccer]] team that played in the [[Women's United Soccer Association]]. The team played at [[Villanova Stadium]] on the campus of [[Villanova University]] near [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].\n\n==History==\nIn spring of 2000, the newly formed [[Women's United Soccer Association]] (WUSA) announced eight cities were granted franchises to start the league, including [[Philadelphia]].<ref name=founded/> Most of the inaugural teams were owned by major media companies, with the new Philadelphia club operated by locally headquartered [[Comcast Corporation]] who invested an initial $5 million into WUSA.<ref name=founded/><ref name=Comcast>{{cite web |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/stories/2001/04/09/story8.html |title=Women's soccer team ready to Charge |author=John George |website=bizjournals.com |date=9 April 2002 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> In November 2000, the club's name and logo was officially announced as the '''Philadelphia Charge''' and would play home matches at [[Villanova Stadium]].<ref name=Announce>{{cite web |url=https://reuters.screenocean.com/record/167354 |title=USA: SOCCER - INAUGURAL WOMEN'S PROFESSIONAL SOCCER LEAGUE ANNOUNCES TEAM NAMES, LOGOS |publisher=Reuters |date=2 November 2000 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> The logo for the Charge incorporated the Comcast Corp. \"C\" as part of its marketing efforts.<ref name=Comcast/> The Charge began preparations for the first team with a 15-person front office and was supported by the Comcast-Spector organization for stadium operations, marketing, promotions, tickets, and merchandise.<ref name=Comcast/>\n\nBy late 2000, the Charge had announced that [[University of Hartford]] women's soccer coach, [[Mark Krikorian (soccer)|Mark Krikorian]], would be appointed the first head coach of the team.<ref name=HirKrikorian>{{cite web |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2000-11-20-0011201736-story.html |title=KRIKORIAN TO TAKE CHARGE OF PHILADELPHIA FRANCHISE |author=Mark Pukalo |publisher=The Hartford Courant |date=20 November 2000 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> Prior to the start of the season, Krikorian would bring on former Swedish international [[Pia Sundhage]] and [[John Natale]] as assistant coaches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/8769/wusa-notes-assistant-coach-and-front-office-hirin.html |title=WUSA Notes: Assistant coach and front-office hirings |publisher=SoccerAmerica |date=1 February 2001 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Charge would begin their first campaign lead by American forward [[Lorrie Fair]], German defender [[Doris Fitschen]], and English forward [[Kelly Smith]].<ref name=Announce/>\n\n==Players==\nSeveral notable U.S. Women's National Team stars made their pro debuts with the Charge, including defender [[Heather Mitts]] (2001-2003) and goalkeeper [[Hope Solo]], who appeared in 8 matches as a rookie backup goalkeeper in 2003.  Other notables included French international [[Marinette Pichon]], who won the 2002 WUSA Most Valuable Player award for the Charge, and English star [[Kelly Smith]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.funwhileitlasted.net/2012/07/06/june-8-2002-philadelphia-charge-vs-washington-freedom/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-07-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602170941/http://www.funwhileitlasted.net/2012/07/06/june-8-2002-philadelphia-charge-vs-washington-freedom/ |archivedate=2013-06-02 }}</ref>\n\n'''2003 Roster'''<ref>{{cite news|title=2003 Philadelphia Charge Roster|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/wusa/news/2003/philadelphros/|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=21 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=1|nat=USA|pos=GK|name=[[Melissa Moore (soccer)|Melissa Moore]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=2|nat=USA|pos=MF|name=[[Lorrie Fair]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=3|nat=USA|pos=FW|name=[[Emily Burt]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=5|nat=USA|pos=DF|name=[[Karyn Hall]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=6|nat=USA|pos=DF|name=[[Jenny Benson]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=7|nat=FIN|pos=MF|name=[[Anne Makinen]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=8|nat=ENG|pos=FW|name=[[Kelly Smith]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=9|nat=CZE|pos=MF|name=[[Pavl\u00edna \u0160\u010dasn\u00e1]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|nat=USA|pos=FW|name=[[Deliah Arrington]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|nat=FRA|pos=FW|name=[[Marinette Pichon]]}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|nat=USA|pos=MF|name=[[Erin Misaki]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=13|nat=USA|pos=DF|name=[[Heather Mitts]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=14|nat=USA|pos=MF|name=[[Rachel Kruze]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|nat=USA|pos=MF|name=[[Stacey Tullock]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|nat=DEU|pos=MF|name=[[Melanie Hoffmann]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=18|nat=USA|pos=GK|name=[[Hope Solo]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=19|nat=USA|pos=DF|na