\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2001, Philadelphia Charge player, [[Doris Fitschen]] was named WUSA Defender of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Power forward selected as first WUSA MVP|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/wusa/2001/championship/news/2001/08/23/wusa_awards/|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=21 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Philadelphia Charge player, [[Marinette Pichon]] was named WUSA's Most Valuable Player and Offensive Player of the Year and was the co-recipient with [[Mia Hamm]] for Goal of the Year for a scissor kick volley against the [[San Diego Spirit]]. Goalkeeper [[Melissa Moore (soccer)|Melissa Moore]] was awarded Goalkeeper of the Year and [[Stacey Tullock]] was named Rookie of the Year. Coach [[Mark Krikorian (soccer)|Mark Krikorian]] took the honor of WUSA Coach of the Year the same year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Philadelphia's Pichon takes top honor in WUSA awards|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/wusa/2002-08-22-awards_x.htm|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=21 October 2012|date=22 August 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the Charge was awarded the WUSA Team Fair Play Award and defender, [[Jenny Benson]], was named WUSA Humanitarian of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Meinert wins most valuable player|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/wusa/2003-08-21-wusa-awards_x.htm|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=21 October 2012|date=21 August 2003}}</ref>\n\n==League Suspension==\nThe [[Women's United Soccer Association]] announced on September 15, 2003 that it was suspending operations.<ref>{{cite news|title=WUSA ceases operations after three years|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/wusa/2003-09-15-wusa-folds_x.htm|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=21 October 2012|first1=Vicki|last1=Michaelis|date=16 September 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. WNT Responds to Women's United Soccer Association Suspending Operations|url=http://www.ussoccer.com/news/womens-national-team/2003/09/u-s-wnt-responds-to-womens-united-soccer-association-suspending-operations.aspx|publisher=US Soccer|accessdate=21 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Women's association football|Philadelphia|Sports|Association football}}\n* [[Women's professional sports]]\n* [[List of soccer clubs in the United States]]\n* [[Women's association football]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20011217093641/http://www.wusa.com/charge/ Philadelphia Charge website (archive.org)]\n\n{{Women's United Soccer Association}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct soccer clubs in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Women's soccer clubs in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defunct sports teams in Philadelphia|Charge]]\n[[Category:Soccer clubs in Philadelphia|C]]\n[[Category:Soccer clubs in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Women's United Soccer Association teams]]\n[[Category:2000 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:2003 disestablishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Charge]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs disestablished in 2003]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 2000]]\n\n\n{{Pennsylvania-footyclub-stub}}\n", "name_user": "JSafi ToffeeFan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philadelphia_Charge"}
{"title_page": "Infogram", "text_new": "{{Infobox software\n| name = Infogram\n| logo = Infogramlogo.svg\n| genre = [[Infographic]]s\n| license = Free & paid subscriptions\n| website = {{url|https://infogram.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Infogram''' is a web-based [[data visualization]] and [[Infographic|infographics]] platform, created in Riga, Latvia.<ref name=\":0\">Butcher, Mike (2014-02-13). [https://techcrunch.com/2014/02/13/infogr-am-secures-1-8m-to-scale-its-simple-real-time-info-graphics-platform/ \u201cInfogr.am Secures $1.8M To Scale Its Simple Real-Time Info-Graphics Platform\u201d]. ''TechCrunch.'' Retrieved December 19, 2017.</ref>\n\nIt allows people to make and share digital charts, infographics and maps. Infogram offers an intuitive [[WYSIWYG]] editor that converts users\u2019 data into infographics that can be published, embedded or shared. Users do not need coding skills to use this tool; users include newsrooms, marketing teams, governments, educators and students.<ref name=\":1\">Sawer, Paul (2017-05-16). [https://venturebeat.com/2017/05/16/prezi-makes-it-first-acquisition-snaps-up-latvian-data-visualization-startup-infogram/ \u201cPrezi makes its first acquisition, snaps up Latvian data visualization startup Infogram\u201d]. ''VentureBeat.'' Retrieved December 19, 2017.</ref>\n\nThe company that created Infogram, also called Infogram, was founded in 2012 in Riga, Latvia and has another office in San Francisco. As of October 2017, Infogram says it has 3 million users who have created charts and infographics that have been viewed more than 1.5 billion times.<ref>[https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/infogram-announces-new-version-of-leading-data-visualization-platform-300542002.html \u201cInfogram Announces New Version of Leading Data Visualization Platform\u201d]. ''PR Newswire.'' October, 24, 2017. Retrieved December 19, 2017.</ref>\n\nInfogram was bought by Prezi, a web-based presentation software company, in May 2017.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==History==\nInfogram was founded in February 2012 in [[Riga]], [[Latvia]] by [[Uldis Leiterts]], Raimonds Ka\u017ee and [[Alise D\u012brika]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn January 2013, Infogram won the international [http://www.hy.co/ Hy Berlin] pitch contest. During his pitch, Infogram CEO Uldis Leiterts announced that the company had created more templates and was working with Microsoft to integrate its platform with the contemporaneous version of Microsoft Office.<ref>Bryan, Martin (2013-01-19). [https://thenextweb.com/insider/2013/01/19/hy-berlin-pitching-contest/ \u201cEasy infographics, a \u2018GitHub for the real world\u2019 and a Roomba for solar panels win at Hy Berlin\u201d]. ''The Next Web.'' Retrieved December 19, 2017.</ref>\n\nThe company also won the 2013 Kantar Information Is Beautiful Award, which \u201ccelebrates excellence and beauty in data visualizations,\u2009infographics, interactives & \u2009information art.\u201d<ref>[https://thenextweb.com/hardfork/2017/12/06/wikipedia-co-founder-joins-everipedia-to-create-an-encyclopedia-on-the-blockchain/ Kantar Information is Beautiful Awards]. 2013. Retrieved December 19, 2017.</ref><ref>[https://www.informationisbeautifulawards.com/about Kantar Information is Beautiful Awards - About]. Retrieved December 19, 2017.</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, Infogram acquired the Brazil-based data visualization blog, Visualoop.<ref>Sawers, Paul (2014-12-03) [https://venturebeat.com/2014/12/03/infographics-platform-infogr-am-bets-big-on-brazil-as-it-acquires-data-visualization-blog-visualoop/ \u201cInfographics platform Infogr.am bets big on Brazil as it acquires data-visualization blog Visualoop\u201d]. ''VentureBeat.'' Retrieved December 19, 2017.</ref>\n\nIn an effort to expand sales and marketing in the U.S., Infogram secured $1.8 million in funding in February 2014. The announcement was made at [http://tcbaltics.com/ TechChill], a startup conference for the Baltics in Riga, Latvia. At the time, the funding was believed to be the largest to date for the company.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nInfogram won the 2017 National Design Award of Latvia.<ref>National Design Award of Latvia. [http://www.designaward.lv/en/winners/2017/data-visualization-tool-infogram \u201c1st place - Data Visualization Platform \u2018Infogram\u2019\u201d]. 2017. Retrieved December 19, 2017.</ref>\n\n== Acquisition by Prezi ==\n[[Prezi]], a web-based presentation software company, acquired Infogram in May 2017. Infogram is now a wholly owned subsidiary of Prezi.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nInfogram was rated #1 on Forbes\u2019 list of \u201cThe Best Infographic Tools for 2017,\u201d which was published in September 2017.<ref>Marr, Bernard (2017-09-17). [https://www.forbes.com/sites/bernardmarr/2017/09/16/data-visualization-the-best-infographic-tools-for-2017/#64f5f5b57d24 \u201cData Visualization: The Best Infographic Tools For 2017\u201d]. ''Fortune.'' Retrieved December 19, 2017.</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Infogram announced a new version of its data visualization platform, including a drag-and-drop editor, over 40 new designer templates and social media support.<ref>[http://www.econtentmag.com/Articles/News/News-Item/Infogram-Announces-New-Version-of-Data-Visualization-Platform-121336.htm \u201cInfogram Announces New Version of Data Visualization Platform\u201d]. EContent. October 26, 2017. Retrieved December 19, 2017.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[https://infogram.com/examples Infogram examples]\n*[[Infographics]]\n*[[Data visualization]]\n*[[Chart]]\n*[[Data-driven journalism]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Latvian brands]]\n[[Category:Data visualization software]]\n[[Category:Graphics software]]\n[[Category:Collaborative software]]\n[[Category:Web applications]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox software\n| name = Infogram\n| logo = Infogramlogo.svg\n| genre = [[Infographic]]s\n| license = Free & paid subscriptions\n| website = {{url|https://www.telegram.me/IG_R0BOT}}\n}}\n\n'''Infogram''' is a web-based [[data visualization]] and [[Infographic|infographics]] platform, created in Riga, Latvia.<ref name=\":0\">Butcher, Mike (2014-02-13). [https://techcrunch.com/2014/02/13/infogr-am-secures-1-8m-to-scale-its-simple-real-time-info-graphics-platform/ \u201cInfogr.am Secures $1.8M To Scale Its Simple Real-Time Info-Graphics Platform\u201d]. ''TechCrunch.'' Retrieved December 19, 2017.</ref>\n\nIt allows people to make and share digital charts, infographics and maps. Infogram offers an intuitive [[WYSIWYG]] editor that converts users\u2019 data into infographics that can be published, embedded or shared. Users do not need coding skills to use this tool; users include newsrooms, marketing teams, governments, educators and students.<ref name=\":1\">Sawer, Paul (2017-05-16). [https://venturebeat.com/2017/05/16/prezi-makes-it-first-acquisition-snaps-up-latvian-data-visualization-startup-infogram/ \u201cPrezi makes its first acquisition, snaps up Latvian data visualization startup Infogram\u201d]. ''VentureBeat.'' Retrieved December 19, 2017.</ref>\n\nThe company that created Infogram, also called Infogram, was founded in 2012 in Riga, Latvia and has another office in San Francisco. As of October 2017, Infogram says it has 3 million users who have created charts and infographics that have been viewed more than 1.5 billion times.<ref>[https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/infogram-announces-new-version-of-leading-data-visualization-platform-300542002.html \u201cInfogram Announces New Version of Leading Data Visualization Platform\u201d]. ''PR Newswire.'' October, 24, 2017. Retrieved December 19, 2017.</ref>\n\nInfogram was bought by Prezi, a web-based presentation software company, in May 2017.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==History==\nInfogram was founded in February 2012 in [[Riga]], [[Latvia]] by [[Uldis Leiterts]], Raimonds Ka\u017ee and [[Alise D\u012brika]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn January 2013, Infogram won the international [http://www.hy.co/ Hy Berlin] pitch contest. During his pitch, Infog